# defining all the functions here
def filter_airports(df,name):
    airport_cancelled = pd.DataFrame(df.groupby(name)['Cancelled'].sum()).reset_index()
    airport_count = pd.DataFrame(df[name].value_counts()).reset_index()
    airport_count.columns = [name, 'Count']
    airport_cancelled_count = pd.merge(airport_cancelled, airport_count, on = name )
    airport_cancelled_count=airport_cancelled_count.sort_values('Cancelled', ascending=False)
    list_of_airport = airport_cancelled_count[name].to_list()
    return(list_of_airport)


# function to evaluate a decision tree model
def evaluate_model(dt_classifier):
    print("Train Accuracy :", accuracy_score(Y_train, dt_classifier.predict(X_train)))
    print("Train Confusion Matrix:")
    confusion(Y_train,dt_classifier.predict(X_train))
    print('AUC:',roc_auc_score(Y_train,dt_classifier.predict(X_train)))
    print("-"*50)
    print("Test Accuracy :", accuracy_score(Y_test, dt_classifier.predict(X_test)))
    print("Test Confusion Matrix:")
    confusion(Y_test, dt_classifier.predict(X_test))
    print('AUC:',roc_auc_score(Y_test,dt_classifier.predict(X_test)))
    print(classification_report(Y_test,dt_classifier.predict(X_test)))


# function to plot confusion matrices for all the classification problems    
def confusion(Y,X):
    cf_matrix = confusion_matrix(Y,X)
    group_names = ['True Neg','False Pos','False Neg','True Pos']
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in cf_matrix.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf_matrix.flatten()/np.sum(cf_matrix)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}\n{v3}" for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_names,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    sns.heatmap(cf_matrix, annot=labels, fmt='', cmap='Blues')
    plt.show()
    
    
# plotting the decision tree
def get_dt_graph(dt_classifier):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(30,20))
    _ = tree.plot_tree(dt_classifier,
                       feature_names=X_train.columns,
                       class_names=['Not Cancelled', "Cancelled"],
                       filled=True)
    
# converting time to hour
def hour_convert(data,column):
    data[column] = data[column].div(100).round(2)#getting only the hours
    data[column] = data[column].astype('str')
    split_data = df[column].apply(lambda x:x.split(".")[0])
    df[column] = split_data
    
    

def draw_roc( actual, probs ):
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = metrics.roc_curve( actual, probs,drop_intermediate = False )
    auc_score = metrics.roc_auc_score( actual, probs )
    plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
    plt.plot( fpr, tpr, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % auc_score )
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate or [1 - True Negative Rate]')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic example')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()
    return None

Decision Tree Classification¶

Decision trees can be used for classification as well as regression problems. The name itself suggests that it uses a flowchart like a tree structure to show the predictions that result from a series of feature-based splits. It starts with a root node and ends with a decision made by leaves. We will select a few parameters and assign a range to them to feed in for cross validation. we do this to get the best parameter values to put into the model while fitting it and then testing it on test data. Here the parameters taken into consideration are depth of the tree, number of leaves and the criteria of split, gini or impurity (entropy). Through cross validation, we will concentrate on scoring through recall, since we need the accuracy of predicting the "True Positives".

Random Forest Classifier¶

The random forest method determines the outcome based on decision tree forecasts. It forecasts by averaging or averaging the output of various trees. The precision of the result improves as the number of trees grows. It's an ensemble learning technique in which numerous decision trees collaborate and their conclusions are voted on to make the final classification choice. To improve the prediction of genuine negatives, we will tweak parameters such as max depth, estimators, and features in this method. (class 1 cancellation)

Logistic Classification with and without Lasso/Ridge penalty¶

Logistic regression is a surpervised classification method, which assumes linear relationship between x and y.Lasso tends to do well if there are a small number of significant parameters and the others are close to zero (ergo: when only a few predictors actually influence the response). Ridge works well if there are many large parameters of about the same value (ergo: when most predictors impact the response).

XG BOOST CLASSIFICATION¶

The gradient boosted trees algorithm is implemented in XGBoost, a popular and efficient open-source implementation. Gradient boosting is a supervised learning approach that combines the estimates of a set of smaller, weaker models to attempt to accurately predict a target variable. The weak learners in gradient boosting for regression are regression trees, and each regression tree transfers an input data point to one of its leafs containing a continuous score. XGBoost combines a convex loss function (based on the difference between the anticipated and target outputs) with a penalty term for model complexity to minimise a regularised (L1 and L2) objective function (in other words, the regression tree functions). The training process is repeated iteratively, with new trees being added that forecast the residuals or errors of previous trees, which are then integrated with previous trees to provide the final prediction. Gradient boosting gets its name from the fact that it employs a gradient descent algorithm.

# explore xgboost tree depth effect on performance 
# get a list of models to evaluate
def get_models():
    models = dict()
    for i in range(1,11):
        models[str(i)] = XGBClassifier(max_depth=i)
    return models
 
# evaluate a give model using cross-validation
def evaluate_model(model):
    cv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=4, n_repeats=3, random_state=1)
    scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train, Y_train, scoring='recall', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1)
    return scores
 
# get the models to evaluate
models = get_models()
# evaluate the models and store results
results, names = list(), list()
for name, model in models.items():
    scores = evaluate_model(model)
    results.append(scores)
    names.append(name)
    print('>%s %.3f (%.3f)' % (name, mean(scores), std(scores)))
# plot model performance for comparison
pyplot.boxplot(results, labels=names, showmeans=True)
pyplot.show()

# get a list of learning rates to evaluate
def get_models():
    models = dict()
    rates = [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1.0]
    for r in rates:
        key = '%.4f' % r
        models[key] = XGBClassifier(eta=r)
    return models

# evaluate a give model using cross-validation
def evaluate_model(model):

    scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train, Y_train, scoring='recall', cv=cv, n_jobs=-1)
    return scores

Support Vector Machines¶

The support vector machine algorithm's goal is to find a hyperplane in an N-dimensional space (N the number of features) that distinguishes between data points. There are numerous hyperplanes from which to choose to separate the two classes of data points. Our goal is to discover a plane with the greatest margin, or the greatest distance between data points from both classes. Maximizing the margin distance gives some reinforcement, making it easier to classify subsequent data points. Due to computational time limits, CV was not attainable on SVM.

Neural Network¶

The convolutional neural network (CNN) is a class of deep learning neural networks. CNNs represent a huge breakthrough in image recognition. They're most commonly used to analyze visual imagery and are frequently working behind the scenes in image classification. The network used bellow, has 5 sequential layers and uses the Adam optimizer with loss function of binary cross entropy. The final layer activation function is that of sigmoid, since it is a classification problem¶

In [69]:

In [163]:
import time
start = time.time()
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(60,input_dim=input_dim))
model.add(Activation('relu'))

model.add(Dense(60))
model.add(Activation('relu'))

model.add(Dense(60))
model.add(Activation('relu'))

model.add(Dense(output_dim))

model.add(Activation('sigmoid'))#sigmoid

model.compile(optimizer=Adam(),loss='binary_crossentropy',metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()
model.fit(X_resampled,Y_resampled,epochs=700)
prediction_prob = model.predict(x_test_delay)
prediction_class = (prediction_prob > 0.6).astype("int32")

print('Accuracy:', accuracy_score(y_test_delay,prediction_class))
print('AUC:',roc_auc_score(y_test_delay,prediction_prob))
end = time.time()
print(end - start)
In [112]:
def get_feature_importance(j, n):
    s = accuracy_score(y_test_delay, prediction_class) # baseline score
    total = 0.0
    for i in range(n):
        perm = np.random.permutation(range(x_test_delay.shape[0]))
        X_test_ = x_test_delay.copy()
        X_test_.iloc[:, j] = X_test.iloc[perm, j]
        prediction_prob = model.predict(X_test)
        s_ij = accuracy_score(y_test, prediction_prob)
        total += s_ij
    return s - total / n

In [75]:
#Decision Tree for Delay
start = time.time()
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
params = {
    'max_depth': [30,40,45],# total depth the tree can grow, smaller the depth lesser the chances of over fitting the data
    'min_samples_leaf': [8,10,11,12,15],# number of segments, each node can be divided into
    'criterion': ["gini", "entropy"]}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=dt, 
                           param_grid=params, 
                           cv=20, n_jobs=-1, verbose=1, scoring = "recall")

# we are now performing cross validation
grid_search.fit(X_resampled, Y_resampled)

# the values with the best estimator is achieved through cv
print(grid_search.best_estimator_)

dt_best_delay = grid_search.best_estimator_

# now we will perform the evaluation to test the model on test data
print("Train Accuracy :", accuracy_score(Y_resampled, dt_best_delay.predict(X_resampled)))
print("Train Confusion Matrix:")
confusion(Y_resampled,dt_best_delay.predict(X_resampled))
print('AUC:',roc_auc_score(Y_resampled,dt_best_delay.predict(X_resampled)))
print("-"*50)
print("Test Accuracy :", accuracy_score(y_test_delay, dt_best_delay.predict(x_test_delay)))
print("Test Confusion Matrix:")
confusion(y_test_delay, dt_best_delay.predict(x_test_delay))
print('AUC:',roc_auc_score(y_test_delay,dt_best_delay.predict(x_test_delay)))
draw_roc( y_test_delay, dt_best_delay.predict(x_test_delay) )

print(classification_report(y_test_delay, dt_best_delay.predict(x_test_delay)))
end = time.time()
print(end - start)
